Note:
Bash Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the Bash translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    Bash source
      -> bash_lexer    (tokenize: words, quoting, operators, redirections, keywords)
      -> bash_parser   (build Bash AST: commands, pipelines, lists, control flow,
                        function defs, assignments)
      -> bash_to_hir   (lower Bash AST to the canonical bash HIR dict/list model)
      -> hir_to_bash   (emit HIR back to valid Bash text)
      -> re-lex / re-parse / re-to_hir of the emitted text
      -> structural HIR equality on the key constructs

Semantic-stage note: the bash translation pipeline that runs end to end is
lexer -> parser -> to_hir -> backend, identical to the dart programming-language
frontend, whose to_hir lowering likewise does not invoke its semantic analyzer.
bash_semantic.runa is a struct-schema analyzer written against a planned
enriched-HIRNode schema (see its own header comment) and is not wired onto the
flat Integer AST the real parser emits; connecting it is deferred to the
v0.0.9.x semantic-analysis layer. This probe therefore exercises the live
pipeline, matching the sibling programming-language convention.

The probe feeds a representative Bash script that exercises every major
construct the task requires:

  - a function definition (greet)
  - an if statement with a test condition
  - a for loop over a word list
  - a variable assignment with an expansion reference
  - a piped command

It then asserts, on the FIRST HIR tree:
  1. the root is a "script" node with the expected number of top-level commands;
  2. the function-definition node carries the correct function name;
  3. the if-statement, for-loop, variable-assignment, and pipeline nodes are
     present with the correct node-type tags and key payloads (assignment
     target name, command name inside the pipeline).

Then it emits the HIR back to Bash text, re-runs the whole pipeline on the
emitted text, and asserts the re-derived HIR is STRUCTURALLY EQUAL to the
original on those same key constructs. Structural equality (rather than byte
equality) is the correct semantic-equivalence check because the emitter
re-indents and normalises whitespace while the meaning is identical.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.

The bash HIR node model is a string-keyed hashtable (created by
bash_to_hir.create_hir_dict) whose "node_type" key holds the canonical tag
string and whose structural fields ("commands", "name", "items", etc.) hold
either child HIR dicts or HIR lists. This probe therefore reads HIR fields via
the same hashtable_get / list primitives the frontend and backend use, rather
than the canonical HIR literal accessors used by the data-format languages.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/bash/bash_lexer.runa" as BashLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/bash/bash_parser.runa" as BashParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/bash/bash_to_hir.runa" as BashFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/bash/hir_to_bash.runa" as BashBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each round of the probe runs the identical front-of-pipeline (lex -> parse ->
to_hir). Factoring it into one helper keeps the two pipeline runs (original
source and emitted text) identical in behaviour so any structural divergence is
attributable to the emitter, not to a difference in how the two inputs were
driven.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a lexer over the source, wraps it in a parser, drives a full parse to
the Bash AST root, then lowers the AST to HIR via translate_bash_to_hir and
returns the HIR root. Returns 0 if any stage yields 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_bash_lexer from BashLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_parser from BashParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from BashParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_bash_to_hir from BashFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR nodes are string-keyed hashtables, so reading a field is a hashtable_get
with a string-literal key. Wrapping it keeps the assertions readable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to Dict.hashtable_get(node, key). Returns 0 for a missing key or a
null node.
@End Implementation
Process called "field" takes node as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc hashtable_get from Dict with node, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locate the descendant of the HIR tree whose "node_type" matches a requested
tag. The probe must find the function-definition, if-statement, for-loop,
assignment, and pipeline regardless of how the parser nests them: top-level
statements may be direct children of the script's "commands" list, or wrapped
inside a "command_list" node's "items" list, or appear as the body of another
construct. A bounded recursive search by tag is therefore the robust locator -
it descends through the structural container fields (commands, items, body,
then_body) that hold child statements without needing to model the exact
nesting the parser chose.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the node itself matches the tag, returns it. Otherwise recurses, in order,
into: the "commands" list (script/pipeline), the "items" list (command_list),
and the single-child structural fields "body" and "then_body". Returns the
first match found in a depth-first walk, or 0 if no descendant matches. The
walk only follows known structural container fields, so it terminates on the
finite HIR tree.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_node" takes node as Integer, tag as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc field with node, "node_type"
    If node_type is not equal to 0:
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with node_type, tag is equal to 1:
            Return node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Recurse through list-valued structural containers
    Let commands be proc field with node, "commands"
    If commands is not equal to 0:
        Let cc be proc list_length from List with commands
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than cc:
            Let child be proc list_get from List with commands, i
            Let found be proc find_node with child, tag
            If found is not equal to 0:
                Return found
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let items be proc field with node, "items"
    If items is not equal to 0:
        Let ic be proc list_length from List with items
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than ic:
            Let item be proc list_get from List with items, j
            Let found_i be proc find_node with item, tag
            If found_i is not equal to 0:
                Return found_i
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Recurse through single-child structural fields
    Let body be proc field with node, "body"
    If body is not equal to 0:
        Let found_b be proc find_node with body, tag
        If found_b is not equal to 0:
            Return found_b
        End If
    End If

    Let then_body be proc field with node, "then_body"
    If then_body is not equal to 0:
        Let found_t be proc find_node with then_body, tag
        If found_t is not equal to 0:
            Return found_t
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two bash scripts are semantically equal on the constructs the task names when,
for each key construct, both HIR projections expose the same node-type tag and
the same identifying payload (function name, assignment target, pipeline
command name). Comparing these specific fields rather than full byte text is
whitespace- and indentation-insensitive, proving round-trip fidelity without
being defeated by the emitter's re-indentation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 when both nodes are non-null and their "node_type" strings are equal.
Used as the base structural check for each located construct before the probe
drills into the construct-specific payload.
@End Implementation
Process called "same_kind" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ka be proc field with a, "node_type"
    Let kb be proc field with b, "node_type"
    If ka is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If kb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc string_equals from StringCore with ka, kb
End Process

@Reasoning:
The command-list join operator (&&, ||, ;, &) is the payload this probe
must assert directly, because the four operators lower to a single
"command_list" HIR shape and a symmetric re-parse equality check cannot
tell them apart - that symmetry is exactly what previously hid the loss of
the operator. The fix records each join operator in the command_list's
parallel "operators" list, so the probe reads that tag directly. This
helper locates the first command_list descendant and returns its first
operator string (the operator joining the first two commands), or 0 if no
command_list with operators is present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Locates the top-most command_list via find_node, reads its "operators"
list, and returns operators[0] (a canonical operator string) when the list
is non-null and non-empty. Returns 0 otherwise so callers can assert
presence as well as the specific spelling.
@End Implementation
Process called "first_operator" takes hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list_node be proc find_node with hir, "command_list"
    If list_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let operators be proc field with list_node, "operators"
    If operators is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let op_count be proc list_length from List with operators
    If op_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc list_get from List with operators, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reduces an operator-spelling assertion to a 0/1 the test harness can check:
the located operator string must be non-null AND equal to the expected
spelling. Keeping it separate from first_operator lets the caller assert a
clear failure both when no operator survived (null) and when the wrong
operator survived (mismatch).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if op is 0 (no operator carried). Otherwise returns
string_equals(op, expected): 1 when the carried operator matches the
expected spelling, 0 when a different operator was carried.
@End Implementation
Process called "operator_is" takes op as Integer, expected as Integer returns Integer:
    If op is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc string_equals from StringCore with op, expected
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "Bash translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative script: a function definition, an if with a test condition,
    a for loop over a word list, a variable assignment with an expansion, and a
    piped command. Newlines separate the top-level statements.
    :End Note
    Let source be "function greet { echo hello; }\nif test -f file; then echo yes; fi\nfor x in a b c; do echo $x; done\ncount=value\ncat data | grep needle\n"

    Note: --- Stage 0-2: source -> HIR (lex, parse, lower) ---
    Let lexer be proc create_bash_lexer from BashLexer with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "lexer created", lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from BashParser with lexer
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser created", parser

    Let ast be proc parse from BashParser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser produced Bash AST", ast

    Let hir1 be proc translate_bash_to_hir from BashFrontend with ast
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR root", hir1

    Note: Root must be a "script" node.
    Let root_type be proc field with hir1, "node_type"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR root has node_type", root_type
    Let root_is_script be proc string_equals from StringCore with root_type, "script"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR root is a script node", root_is_script, 1

    Note: Script has a non-empty top-level command list.
    Let top_commands be proc field with hir1, "commands"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "script has commands list", top_commands
    Let top_count be proc list_length from List with top_commands
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "script has at least 5 top-level statements", top_count, 5

    Note: --- function definition: located by tag, name payload checked ---
    Let func_node be proc find_node with hir1, "function_definition"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function_definition node present", func_node
    Let func_name be proc field with func_node, "name"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function has a name", func_name
    Let func_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func_name, "greet"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is 'greet'", func_name_ok, 1

    Note: --- if statement: located by tag ---
    Let if_node be proc find_node with hir1, "if_statement"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if_statement node present", if_node
    Let if_cond be proc field with if_node, "condition"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement has a condition", if_cond

    Note: --- for loop: located by tag, loop variable name checked ---
    Let for_node be proc find_node with hir1, "for_loop"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "for_loop node present", for_node
    Let for_var be proc field with for_node, "variable"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "for loop has a loop variable", for_var
    Let for_var_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with for_var, "x"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "for loop variable is 'x'", for_var_ok, 1

    Note: --- variable assignment: located by tag, target name checked ---
    Let assign_node be proc find_node with hir1, "variable_assignment"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "variable_assignment node present", assign_node
    Let assign_target be proc field with assign_node, "variable"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "assignment has a target name", assign_target
    Let assign_target_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with assign_target, "count"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "assignment target is 'count'", assign_target_ok, 1

    Note: --- pipeline: located by tag, first command name checked ---
    Let pipe_node be proc find_node with hir1, "pipeline"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline node present", pipe_node
    Let pipe_cmds be proc field with pipe_node, "commands"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline has a commands list", pipe_cmds
    Let pipe_cmd_count be proc list_length from List with pipe_cmds
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "pipeline has at least 2 stages", pipe_cmd_count, 2
    Let pipe_first be proc list_get from List with pipe_cmds, 0
    Let pipe_first_name be proc field with pipe_first, "name"
    Let pipe_first_word be proc field with pipe_first_name, "value"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline first command has a name word", pipe_first_word
    Let pipe_first_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with pipe_first_word, "cat"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "pipeline first command is 'cat'", pipe_first_ok, 1

    Note: --- Stage 4: HIR -> Bash text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced Bash text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted Bash is non-empty", emitted_len, 0
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with emitted, 0
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted Bash begins with '#' (shebang)", first_char, 35

    Note: --- Stage 5: re-run the pipeline on the emitted text -> HIR2 ---
    Let hir2 be proc source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted Bash produced HIR", hir2

    Note: Root of the re-derived tree is also a script node.
    Let root2_type be proc field with hir2, "node_type"
    Let root2_is_script be proc string_equals from StringCore with root2_type, "script"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip HIR root is a script node", root2_is_script, 1

    Note: --- Stage 6: structural equality on the key constructs ---
    Let func2 be proc find_node with hir2, "function_definition"
    Let func_kind_ok be proc same_kind with func_node, func2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function_definition node", func_kind_ok, 1
    Let func2_name be proc field with func2, "name"
    Let func2_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func2_name, "greet"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function name 'greet'", func2_name_ok, 1

    Let if2 be proc find_node with hir2, "if_statement"
    Let if_kind_ok be proc same_kind with if_node, if2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves if_statement node", if_kind_ok, 1

    Let for2 be proc find_node with hir2, "for_loop"
    Let for_kind_ok be proc same_kind with for_node, for2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves for_loop node", for_kind_ok, 1
    Let for2_var be proc field with for2, "variable"
    Let for2_var_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with for2_var, "x"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves for loop variable 'x'", for2_var_ok, 1

    Let assign2 be proc find_node with hir2, "variable_assignment"
    Let assign_kind_ok be proc same_kind with assign_node, assign2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves variable_assignment node", assign_kind_ok, 1
    Let assign2_target be proc field with assign2, "variable"
    Let assign2_target_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with assign2_target, "count"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves assignment target 'count'", assign2_target_ok, 1

    Let pipe2 be proc find_node with hir2, "pipeline"
    Let pipe_kind_ok be proc same_kind with pipe_node, pipe2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves pipeline node", pipe_kind_ok, 1
    Let pipe2_cmds be proc field with pipe2, "commands"
    Let pipe2_first be proc list_get from List with pipe2_cmds, 0
    Let pipe2_first_name be proc field with pipe2_first, "name"
    Let pipe2_first_word be proc field with pipe2_first_name, "value"
    Let pipe2_first_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with pipe2_first_word, "cat"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves pipeline first command 'cat'", pipe2_first_ok, 1

    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Statement-drop regression (#511): a function whose body contains an
    Note: assignment, FOLLOWED by additional top-level statements, must keep
    Note: every following statement. Before the fix, the unconsumed '=' inside
    Note: the body poisoned the top-level loop and dropped everything after the
    Note: function. The script below has FOUR top-level statements: the function
    Note: definition, then three plain commands. All four must survive, and the
    Note: post-function assignment target must still be reachable.
    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------
    Let nodrop_source be "function setup { config=on; echo $config; }\nsetup\nresult=ready\necho $result\n"
    Let nodrop_hir be proc source_to_hir with nodrop_source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: pipeline produced HIR", nodrop_hir
    Let nodrop_cmds be proc field with nodrop_hir, "commands"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: script has commands list", nodrop_cmds
    Let nodrop_count be proc list_length from List with nodrop_cmds
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: all four top-level statements survive", nodrop_count, 4

    Note: The function definition (first statement) is intact with its name.
    Let nodrop_func be proc find_node with nodrop_hir, "function_definition"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: function_definition present", nodrop_func
    Let nodrop_func_name be proc field with nodrop_func, "name"
    Let nodrop_func_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with nodrop_func_name, "setup"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: function name is 'setup'", nodrop_func_ok, 1

    Note: The post-function assignment (`result=ready`) survived and is reachable.
    Let nodrop_assign be proc find_node with nodrop_hir, "variable_assignment"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: post-function assignment present", nodrop_assign

    Note: The in-body assignment (`config=on`) lowered to an assignment node too,
    Note: proving the function body itself parsed fully rather than truncating.
    Let nodrop_func_body be proc field with nodrop_func, "body"
    Let nodrop_body_assign be proc find_node with nodrop_func_body, "variable_assignment"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "no-drop: in-body assignment parsed", nodrop_body_assign

    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Declaration round-trip (#511): `local`/`declare`/`unset` now surface as
    Note: command nodes that lower to HIR commands and re-emit faithfully.
    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------
    Let decl_source be "function f { local x=1; declare y; }\n"
    Let decl_hir be proc source_to_hir with decl_source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "declaration: pipeline produced HIR", decl_hir
    Let decl_func be proc find_node with decl_hir, "function_definition"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "declaration: function present", decl_func
    Let decl_emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with decl_hir
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "declaration: backend emitted text", decl_emitted
    Let decl_hir2 be proc source_to_hir with decl_emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "declaration: re-parse of emitted text produced HIR", decl_hir2
    Let decl_func2 be proc find_node with decl_hir2, "function_definition"
    Let decl_kind_ok be proc same_kind with decl_func, decl_func2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "declaration: round-trip preserves the function carrying local/declare", decl_kind_ok, 1

    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Command-list operator preservation (#512): &&, ||, ;, & must each
    Note: survive the full lex -> parse -> to_hir -> backend -> re-parse cycle
    Note: as their own operator, NOT collapse to a single separator. These
    Note: assertions read the carried operator tag in the command_list's
    Note: "operators" list rather than re-parse structural equality, because
    Note: symmetric structural equality is exactly what previously masked the
    Note: loss (all four operators produced the same operator-less AST_LIST).
    Note: Each operator is checked both after the initial lowering AND after
    Note: the emit/re-parse round trip, and the cross-operator negative
    Note: assertions prove `&&` does not degrade into `;`.
    Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------

    Note: --- && (short-circuit-and) ---
    Let and_hir be proc source_to_hir with "a && b\n"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "operator: && source produced HIR", and_hir
    Let and_op be proc first_operator with and_hir
    Let and_is_and be proc operator_is with and_op, "&&"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: && lowered to '&&' tag", and_is_and, 1
    Let and_not_semi be proc operator_is with and_op, ";"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: && did NOT degrade to ';'", and_not_semi, 0
    Let and_emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with and_hir
    Let and_hir2 be proc source_to_hir with and_emitted
    Let and_op2 be proc first_operator with and_hir2
    Let and_rt_ok be proc operator_is with and_op2, "&&"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: && round-trips as '&&'", and_rt_ok, 1

    Note: --- || (short-circuit-or) ---
    Let or_hir be proc source_to_hir with "a || b\n"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "operator: || source produced HIR", or_hir
    Let or_op be proc first_operator with or_hir
    Let or_is_or be proc operator_is with or_op, "||"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: || lowered to '||' tag", or_is_or, 1
    Let or_not_semi be proc operator_is with or_op, ";"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: || did NOT degrade to ';'", or_not_semi, 0
    Let or_emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with or_hir
    Let or_hir2 be proc source_to_hir with or_emitted
    Let or_op2 be proc first_operator with or_hir2
    Let or_rt_ok be proc operator_is with or_op2, "||"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: || round-trips as '||'", or_rt_ok, 1

    Note: --- ; (sequence) ---
    Let seq_hir be proc source_to_hir with "a ; b\n"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "operator: ; source produced HIR", seq_hir
    Let seq_op be proc first_operator with seq_hir
    Let seq_is_semi be proc operator_is with seq_op, ";"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: ; lowered to ';' tag", seq_is_semi, 1
    Let seq_emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with seq_hir
    Let seq_hir2 be proc source_to_hir with seq_emitted
    Let seq_op2 be proc first_operator with seq_hir2
    Let seq_rt_ok be proc operator_is with seq_op2, ";"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: ; round-trips as ';'", seq_rt_ok, 1

    Note: --- & (background) ---
    Let bg_hir be proc source_to_hir with "a & b\n"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "operator: & source produced HIR", bg_hir
    Let bg_op be proc first_operator with bg_hir
    Let bg_is_amp be proc operator_is with bg_op, "&"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: & lowered to '&' tag", bg_is_amp, 1
    Let bg_not_semi be proc operator_is with bg_op, ";"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: & did NOT degrade to ';'", bg_not_semi, 0
    Let bg_emitted be proc generate_bash_from_hir from BashBackend with bg_hir
    Let bg_hir2 be proc source_to_hir with bg_emitted
    Let bg_op2 be proc first_operator with bg_hir2
    Let bg_rt_ok be proc operator_is with bg_op2, "&"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "operator: & round-trips as '&'", bg_rt_ok, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
